'''Zuigaku Rempo Niwa Zenji ''' (1905&ndash;1993)<ref name="bio">{{cite web|title=Niwa, Zuigaku Rempô|url=http://sweepingzen.com/niwa-zuigaku-rempo-bio/|publisher=Sweeping Zen|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref> was a Japanese [[Zen]] master.<ref name="bio"/>
==Biography== Rempo Zenji was born in [[Shizuoka, Shizuoka|Shizuoka]], [[Japan]].<ref name="dogensangha">{{cite web|title=Dogen Sangha (4) The Two Reverend Masters |url=http://gudoblog-e.blogspot.com/2006/08/dogen-sangha-4-two-reverend-masters.html|publisher=[[Gudō Wafu Nishijima]]|date=August 15, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref> His father was a schoolmaster and his mother was a farmer.<ref name="dogensangha"/> After graduating from [[Tokyo University]], he became the head official in Tokei-in<ref name="dogensangha"/> and later studied at [[Antai-ji]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Weitsman|first1=Mel|authorlink1=Mel Weitsman|last2=Wenger|first2=Michael|authorlink2=Michael Wenger|last3=Okumura|first3=Shōhaku|authorlink3=Shōhaku Okumura|title=Dogen Zenji's Shobogenzo Genjo-koan|publisher=|year=|page=132|ISBN=9781582437439}}</ref> At the age of 50,<ref name="larbredeleveil">{{cite web | url=http://larbredeleveil.org/maitres_esp.htm | title=Qué es lo que usted desearía saber a propósito del templo | accessdate=19 December 2014|language= Spanish}}</ref> Niwa became the 77th abbot of the Eihei-ji monastery.<ref name="bio"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Victoria|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Victoria|title=[[Zen at War]]|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|year=2006|page= xiii|ISBN=9780742539266}}</ref> He also received the imperial title of Jikô Enkai Zenji (“Great Zen Master of Compassion, Ocean of Plenitude”).<ref name="bio"/>
An avid practitioner of zazen, he rebuilt the [[zendo]] (meditation hall) so that the young people in training could better engage in this essential practice.<ref name="larbredeleveil"/> His dharma heirs include [[Gudō Wafu Nishijima]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Warner|first=Brad|authorlink=Brad Warner|title=[[Hardcore Zen|Hardcore Zen: Punk Rock, Monster Movies and the Truth About Reality]]|publisher=[[Wisdom Publications]]|year=2003|page=52|ISBN=0-86171-380-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OBITUARY: Gudo Wafu Nishijima|url=http://sweepingzen.com/obituary-gudo-wafu-nishijima/|publisher=Sweeping Zen|date=January 30, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref> and [[Moriyama Daigyo]] as well as several teachers affiliated with the [[Taisen Deshimaru]] Lineage in Europe.<ref name="bio"/> [[Zenji]] (literally, "Zen Master") is an honorary title given to the senior Eihei temple (Eihei-ji), headquarters of the [[Sōtō]] school, founded in the thirteenth century by Master Dogen.
Outside of Zen, he created brush calligraphy.<ref name="treeleaf">{{cite web|title=About Treeleaf and our Lineage|url=http://www.treeleaf.org/about-treeleaf-teachers-jundo-taigu-and-our-lineage/|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref> His work was often credited to various [[pseudonyms]].<ref name="treeleaf"/> Niwa died in 1993.<ref name="bio"/><ref name="dogensangha"/>
